[
    {
        "content": "<p>I am trying to refactor <a href=\"https://github.com/YaelDillies/LeanAPAP/blob/master/LeanAPAP/Prereqs/Convolution/Discrete/Defs.lean\">the definition of discrete convolution I have in APAP</a> to be an <code>abbrev</code> on top of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.convolution#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.convolution</a>. Every lemma is its own battle.</p>",
        "id": 498850118,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1739217368
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Currently I am trying to generalise <a href=\"https://yaeldillies.github.io/LeanAPAP/docs/find/?pattern=smul_conv#doc\">LeanAPAP#smul_conv</a>, which states</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">lemma</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">smul_conv</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">H</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"kt\">Type</span><span class=\"bp\">*</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">DecidableEq</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">AddCommGroup</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">Fintype</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"o\">]</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">CommSemiring</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">DistribSMul</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">H</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">[</span><span class=\"n\">IsScalarTower</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">H</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">]</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">H</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">G</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">→</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">R</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∗</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">c</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">•</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">f</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∗</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">g</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>where <code>∗</code> is the discrete convolution as defined in APAP</p>",
        "id": 498850599,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1739217520
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>The corresponding lemma for <code>MeasureTheory.convolution</code> is <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.smul_convolution#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.smul_convolution</a>, but it only works for <code>y</code> a scalar from the same scalar field of the linear maps, but really it should work for scalars in any subring of that scalar field</p>",
        "id": 498851088,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1739217669
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Tracing it back, <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.integral_smul#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.integral_smul</a> and its preliminary lemmas already aren't properly generalised. Do people have an idea of how hard it would be to generalise the scalars appearing in all those lemmas?</p>",
        "id": 498851543,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1739217812
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>cc <span class=\"user-mention\" data-user-id=\"111080\">@Floris van Doorn</span> since I suspect similar concerns might be coming up in Carleson</p>",
        "id": 498851615,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1739217833
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I'm confused, what do you think the definition of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.integral_smul#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.integral_smul</a> should be?</p>",
        "id": 498855905,
        "sender_full_name": "David Loeffler",
        "timestamp": 1739219305
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>It would be nice if it supported smultiplication by normed rings instead of only fields</p>",
        "id": 498942597,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739258108
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>... or even semirings, eg for <code>n : ℕ</code> we really do want to know the fact that <code>∫ x, n • f x ∂μ = n • ∫ x, f x ∂μ</code></p>",
        "id": 498942981,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1739258326
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think for semirings you might be out of luck because we don't have NormedAddCommMonoid</p>",
        "id": 498943036,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739258360
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I am still hoping... <span aria-label=\"smile\" class=\"emoji emoji-1f642\" role=\"img\" title=\"smile\">:smile:</span></p>",
        "id": 498943164,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1739258411
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I would suggest focusing on just the noncommutativity for now, and see what you get for free as a result</p>",
        "id": 498943265,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739258464
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>I think I looked at this in the past, when I tried to generalize <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=integral_mul_left#doc\">docs#integral_mul_left</a> to quaternions</p>",
        "id": 498943434,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739258538
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh I wasn't hoping for noncommutativity, but that's an interesting thought. All I want is <code>ℕ</code> and <code>ℤ</code></p>",
        "id": 498944309,
        "sender_full_name": "Yaël Dillies",
        "timestamp": 1739258921
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Oh, I'm thinking of <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=integral_mul_const#doc\">docs#integral_mul_const</a> and <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib/pull/19073\">!3#19073</a></p>",
        "id": 498949131,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739260940
    },
    {
        "content": "<p><span class=\"user-mention silent\" data-user-id=\"310045\">Eric Wieser</span> <a href=\"#narrow/channel/287929-mathlib4/topic/Generalising.20docs.23MeasureTheory.2Eintegral_smul/near/498943036\">said</a>:</p>\n<blockquote>\n<p>I think for semirings you might be out of luck because we don't have NormedAddCommMonoid</p>\n</blockquote>\n<p><code>ENormedAddCommMonoid</code> (which is slightly weaker since it also includes <code>ENNReal</code>) coming in <a href=\"https://github.com/leanprover-community/mathlib4/pull/21422\">#21422</a>. Maybe that can be used for this.</p>\n<p>I don't really use scalar subrings of the reals in Carleson. But these generalizations are useful.</p>",
        "id": 498954262,
        "sender_full_name": "Floris van Doorn",
        "timestamp": 1739262878
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Yury and I have discussed <code>NormedAddCommMonoid</code> in the past, but I think we decided that generalizing a bunch of results to TVS first makes such a future migration easier</p>",
        "id": 498955312,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739263268
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>My memory of the titular generalization is that you run into trouble with junk values</p>",
        "id": 498956859,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739263851
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>If your <code>f : ℝ → ℝ × ℝ</code> is integrable in the first component but not the second (and therefore as a whole not integrable), then an action that projects out one component violates the theorem you want</p>",
        "id": 498957189,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739263950
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>You can probably make it work by requiring <code>IsUnit c ∨ c = 0</code> but that's pretty ugly</p>",
        "id": 498957410,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739264032
    },
    {
        "content": "<p>Or by requiring integrability, since <a href=\"https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/find/?pattern=MeasureTheory.Integrable.smul#doc\">docs#MeasureTheory.Integrable.smul</a> is already at the right generality</p>",
        "id": 498958415,
        "sender_full_name": "Eric Wieser",
        "timestamp": 1739264374
    }
]